caption: Phenomenal food, taste profiles you’ll be hard pressed to find elsewhere, and an incredible, thoughtfully designed atmosphere. Would recommend to anyone looking for a unique, engaging dining experience.

Chi Cha rebranded and turned its hooka lounge into a restaurant and a market - a great pivot during COVID. The food is Peruvian inspired. We had their pork belly sandwich - Peruvian Breakfast on the brunch menu, a Peruvian traditional soup - Aguadio de Pollo (I feel like it’s chive but menu says cilantro - it really elevates the soup), tuna ceviche (very japanese inspired and great flavor emphasizing the earthy tones through soy sauce, wasabi and seasame).  Their cocktails are worth the price and so appetizing.  We got coffee and Nutella empanadas to finish the meal. One takeaway is that, after their rebranding, they have done a great job serving Peruvian food right and well, providing a cozy and lush dinning environment, and offering a creative alternative - a market/cafe where you can grab something home quick.

WE FELT DISRESPECTED!  Pros - The hookah is really good. The drinks were all right too. Really enjoyed the music. Mature crowd.  Cons - The servers were almost always on their phones in the corner smoking hookah, with their backs turned against the customers. That is quite unprofessional in my opinion. Either hubby or I had to wait for our server to turn our way for us to get her attention for more drinks. What really made us mad is when we walked in at 5:50pm, we were told to sit anywhere, which we did. At 10:58pm, a server came to us and said, "we have to move you because we have a group that will spend $1,000 on this table" 😱🤯😡. The minimum individual spending if you want to sit on a table is $45 according to what they have indicated on their hookah menu; our bill was $156.75 so well over their minimum limit. Now this server did not know our spending capacity, or that we had a group of friends coming to join us, which we explained but that did not matter to her or the manager. They offered us 2 seats that would be joining a couple that seemed comfortable in their own space, so umm No!We did not feel like we had to move. If the group did have a reservation, we should have been made aware that the table was reserved or even if they thought we would leave early having come in so early, an option to move to a different table of our choosing earlier in the night, when seats were available, would have been disappointing but sufficed. We were asked to move when the group was already in the doors and already getting upset that they had to wait. No offer to reduce the bill, for the inconvenience, was extended by the manager, he just said "the establishment also has its priorities for bigger groups". We were clearly not a priority and for that, it's unlikely we will ever be back. To add insult to injury, they added a $25 gratuity to the bill. P.s. we spent more that $1,500 where we went to meet our friends.  Conclusion - An okay chill spot if you don't mind unprofessionalism. Remember gratuity is included. Ask if the table is reserved for later if you go in early, so you are not abruptly and rudely asked to move.

IF YOU GO, TAKE CASH!  Beautiful interior, but mediocre food and sub-par drinks, PLUS the very real likelihood for identity theft. My friends who smoked hookah, said it was good and affordable (the happy hour cost was $15).  The interior has been redone. It's dark and comfortable and what you think a hookah lounge should look like. However, their bland and weak drinks, blech food and mediocre service gets them nothing. On top of all this, the server will request your credit card and  driver's license BEFORE you've ordered. This policy is bizarre and looks like nothing more than an opportunity to engage in identity theft.  We went for a happy hour. We had overcooked pre-breaded calamari, a decent burger with cold fries, fresh (but bland) guacamole and fresh tortilla chips.  The second star was for their happy hour hookah priced at $15 before 8pm.
